  <brief_summary>
    <textblock>
      Background: Postoperative Frozen-Shoulder (FS) or adhesive capsulitis is a relatively&#xD;
      frequent complication (5-20%), even after simple arthroscopic shoulder surgeries. The&#xD;
      pathophysiology is still unclear, but psychological factors may play a pivotal role. From&#xD;
      clinical experience, the investigators hypothesized that participants, who are reluctant to&#xD;
      take medications, particularly &quot;pain-killers&quot;, have an increased incidence of postoperative&#xD;
      FS. The investigators retrospectively compared participants with and without postoperative FS&#xD;
      by their attitude towards medication and by depression scale questionnaires.&#xD;
    </textblock>
  </brief_summary>
